snippet.title: GMO eggplant reduces pesticide use
snippet.description:
Read the paper here: 
https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0205713

A new study confirms that genetically modified, pest-resistant Bt eggplant (brinjal) has helped smallholder farmers in Bangladesh greatly reduce their use of insecticides, while increasing their incomes six-fold. Infographic by http://www.wenceslaoalmazan.com.

snippet.title: It is time: Using biotechnology to fight pests
snippet.description:
Africa has for many years remained a conservative continent but there appears to be a new wind blowing for the application of technological innovation to agricultural production. The continent is gradually opening up to the idea that biotechnology could play a key role in helping farmers overcome a number of the challenges they are grappling with now. The continent has been battered this year by the Fall Armyworm pests, prompting a push for new innovations to ensure food security. In this video “ITS IS TIME,” we explore the difference biotechnology can make in the fight against the pests.

#biotechnology #fallarmyworm #farming

snippet.title: Pursuing a Dream: Tackling Climate Change and Soil Salinity
snippet.description:
Professors Ashwani and Sneh Lata Pareek work to find new ways for crops to survive in drought and low water (high salinity) areas. This is not just a problem for India, but one that is being seen around the world. But for Professor Ashwani Pareek, this is personal: His home village is one of the areas hardest hit by these changing climatic conditions. Together with his wife, their dream is to breed new varieties of crops that can withstand these conditions, so that farmers in his home village can once again grow crops and vegetables.

#climatechange #farming #agriculture

snippet.title: Fixing the Nitrogen Problem
snippet.description:
Nitrogen fertilizers are a miracle of modern agriculture —  their application increases crop yields which help feed an expanding global population. But there is a downside to the use of nitrogen fertilizers: they require intense amounts of energy to produce; nitrogen runoff is a major source of pollution; and nitrogen is an expensive, often inaccessible input for smallholder farmers around the world. 

Scientists on the Engineering Nitrogen Symbiosis for Africa (ENSA) research project are focused on using biological nitrogen fixation to sustainably increase yields for smallholder farmers in sub-Saharan Africa. By studying the natural nitrogen fixation process in legumes and transferring that process to cereal crops, scientist hope to reduce our reliance on artificial fertilizers. 

Partner institutes on the ENSA project include the John Innes Centre (UK), Aarhus University (Denmark), the Boyce Thompson Institute (US), the Donald Danforth Plant Science Centre (UK), and the French National Institute for Agricultural Research (INRA, France).

ENSA is funded by the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation.

#nitrogen #agriculture #farming

Pamela and her team are working to produce a root rot-resistant bean variety that will greatly impact the lives of many farmers and their families.
